%S A394618 1,1,1,2,1,2,1,5,2,2,1,5,1,2,1,14,1,5,1,5,2,2,1,15,2,2,5,4,1,4,1,51,1,
%T A394618 2,1,14,1,2,2,14,1,6,1,4,2,2,1,52,2,5,1,5,1,15,2,13,2,2,1,13,1,2,4,
%U A394618 266,1,4,1,5,1,4,1,50,1,2,3,4,1,6,1,52,15,2,1,15,1,2,1,12
%N A394618 Number of 5-generated groups of order n: groups that have a generating set of size <= 5.
%C A394618 a(n) = A000001(n) whenever n has at most five prime factors since all non-cyclic simple groups are generated by 2 elements, and if G=HK then the size of the minimum generating set of G is at most the sum of the sizes of minimum generating sets of H and K.
%C A394618 a(n) first differs from A066389 when n=8, from A396721 when n=16 and from A394617 when n=32.
%H A394618 Adam Onus, <a href="/A394618/b394618.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..511</a>
%H A394618 Rashid Barket, Enrico Grimaldi, Yacoub Hendi, Edward Hirst, Adam Onus, and Harmeet Singh, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.12026">Learning the Graphical Nature of Symmetries</a>, arXiv:2607.12026 [stat.ML], 2026. See p. 9.
%e A394618 a(p) = 1 for p prime since the unique group of order p is cyclic.
%e A394618 a(32) = 51 because there are 51 groups of order 32 and all can be generated by five elements.
%e A394618 a(64) = 266 because there are 267 groups of order 64 and only (C_2)^6 cannot be generated by five elements.
%o A394618 (SageMath) lambda n : sum([len(sage.interfaces.gap.gap.MinimalGeneratingSet(G)) <= 5 for G in sage.interfaces.gap.gap(n).AllSmallGroups()])
%Y A394618 Cf. A000001, A066389, A396721, A394617.
%K A394618 nonn,new
%O A394618 1,4
%A A394618 _Adam Onus_, Jun 18 2026
